<p><h1><b><u>Is,Are</u></b></h1><br>
<h4><ol start="1. ">
<li>We use <b>is</b> with singular nouns and pronouns.<br><br>
<p>The chair<b> is </b>old.<br>
<p>The train <b>is</b> late.<br>
<p>He <b> is</b> a postman.<br>
<li>We use <b>are</b> with plural nouns and pronouns.<br><br>
<p>These chairs <b>are</b> old.<br>
<p>All the trains <b>are</b> late.<br>
<p>They <b>are</b> students of this school<br><br>
<p><b>However, there are two important points to remember...</b><br><br>
<li>I is also a singular pronoun. With  I  we use <b>am</b><br><br>
<p>I <b>am</b> your friend. I <b>am</b> very hungry.<br>
<li>With you, we always use <b>are</b>, whether you stands for one person or for more than one person:<br><br>
<p>You <b>are</b> a student. ( You for one student)<br>
<p>You <b>are</b> students. ( you for more than one student)<br>	
</h4>
